# Creating Endpoints in OpenFusionAPI

This manual focuses exclusively on the **creation of endpoints** in `OpenFusionAPI`.  
Each step below corresponds to an image to help guide you visually through the configuration process.

---

## 1. Selecting the Application

Before creating an endpoint, you must select an existing application from the dropdown menu at the top.  
Once selected, the list of endpoints associated with that application will be loaded.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## 2. Creating a New Endpoint

On the **Endpoints** tab, click the **“New”** icon to create a new endpoint.  
This will open the endpoint creation form.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## 3. Filling Out Basic Endpoint Information

In the form shown in the third image, you need to configure the following fields:

- **API Resource:** Define the path of the endpoint and select the environment at the end of the route.  
- **Handler:** Choose one of the available handlers.  
- **Access:** Set the access level (e.g., Public, Bearer, etc.).  
- **Method:** Select the HTTP method the endpoint will use.  
- **Timeout Cache:** Set the cache time in seconds (0 disables caching).  
- **Description:** Describe the purpose of the endpoint. This is especially useful if the endpoint will be used as an MCP tool.

A green message at the bottom will indicate whether the URL is valid.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## 4. Additional Configuration Tabs

Once the handler is selected, more configuration tabs are displayed depending on the handler type.  
For example, the **SQL** handler enables several additional configuration tabs.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## 5. Documentation Tab

Most handlers include a **Documentation** tab, where you will find specific information about how the handler works.  
This is helpful for maintaining clear technical documentation directly associated with each endpoint.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## 6. JSON Schema Tab

The **JSON Schema** tab defines the expected structure of the input data.  
This information is crucial when the endpoint is used as an MCP tool, as it informs the AI of the exact data structure required.  
Refer to [https://json-schema.org/](https://json-schema.org/) for more information about the format.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## 7. MCP Tab (Model Context Protocol)

The **MCP** tab allows you to enable the endpoint as an MCP tool.  
Here you can set the tool name, title, and description — providing AI systems with the context they need to understand how to use the endpoint.

![Screenshot](data:image/png;base64,)

---

## ✅ Final Notes

- Ensure that the **API Resource** URL is valid and clearly defined.  
- Add a **meaningful description** to support MCP usage.  
- Complete the **JSON Schema** if the endpoint will be exposed as a tool.  
- Configure MCP fields properly to ensure smooth AI integration.

---

📌 *This manual covers only the creation of endpoints. Application creation is documented separately.*
